# Descriptive performance

## Participant-level mean absolute error

```{r participant-summary-table}
participant_summary <- value_participant |>
  group_by(stat_type, group, lecture_type, practice_type) |>
  summarise(
    n = n(),
    mean_abs_error = mean(mean_abs_error, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_abs_error = sd(mean_abs_error, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_abs_error = median(mean_abs_error, na.rm = TRUE),
    mean_sign_error_rate = mean(sign_error_rate, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |>
  mutate(
    stat_type = recode(as.character(stat_type), correlation = "Correlation", slope = "Slope")
  ) |>
  arrange(stat_type, group)

pretty_table(participant_summary, caption = "Participant-level value-estimation performance by condition")
```

```{r participant-error-plot, fig.height=5.5}
ggplot(value_participant, aes(x = group, y = mean_abs_error, color = group)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.12, alpha = 0.55, size = 1.8) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", color = "black", size = 3) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_normal, geom = "errorbar", color = "black", width = 0.18) +
  facet_wrap(~ stat_type, scales = "free_y", labeller = as_labeller(c(correlation = "Correlation estimation", slope = "Slope estimation"))) +
  scale_color_manual(values = GROUP_COLORS, guide = "none") +
  labs(
    title = "Participant-level value-estimation error",
    subtitle = "Each colored point is one participant. Black points show condition means with normal-approximation CIs.",
    x = "Condition",
    y = "Mean absolute error"
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(color = "gray35")
  )
```

The first thing to look for here is whether the condition pattern is visually large compared with participant-to-participant variability. If the colored points overlap heavily across conditions, then even visible mean differences should be treated cautiously.

## Sign errors

Sign errors are only meaningful when the correct value is nonzero. I keep this as a secondary descriptive check because it captures a different kind of mistake: getting the direction wrong rather than simply being numerically far away.

```{r sign-error-summary}
sign_summary <- value_item |>
  filter(!is.na(sign_error), correct_answer != 0) |>
  group_by(stat_type, group) |>
  summarise(
    n_participants = n_distinct(participantId),
    n_scored_trials = n(),
    n_sign_errors = sum(sign_error, na.rm = TRUE),
    sign_error_rate = n_sign_errors / n_scored_trials,
    .groups = "drop"
  ) |>
  mutate(
    stat_type = recode(as.character(stat_type), correlation = "Correlation", slope = "Slope"),
    sign_error_rate = fmt_pct(sign_error_rate, accuracy = 0.1)
  ) |>
  arrange(stat_type, group)

pretty_table(sign_summary, caption = "Sign errors by condition")
```

```{r sign-error-note}
cat(
  '<div class="note-box">',
  '<p><strong>How to read this table.</strong> Here <code>n_sign_errors</code> is the count of trials where the participant gave the wrong sign. ',
  '<code>n_scored_trials</code> is the number of nonzero-answer trials used as the denominator. ',
  'I report sign error this way because the participant-level <code>n</code> can be confusing: each condition has 20 participants, but the sign-error question is really about how many responses had the wrong direction.</p>',
  '</div>'
)
```

# Correlation value-estimation model

This model uses only the correlation-estimation items.

```{r correlation-model-fit}
corr_item <- value_item |>
  filter(stat_type == "correlation", !is.na(abs_error_no_extreme))

corr_participant <- value_participant |>
  filter(stat_type == "correlation")

m_corr <- lmer(
  abs_error_no_extreme ~ lecture_type * practice_type + (1 | participantId),
  data = corr_item,
  REML = FALSE
)

corr_estimates <- condition_estimates(m_corr, "Correlation absolute error")
```

**Model formula**

```text
abs_error_no_extreme ~ lecture_type * practice_type + (1 | participantId)
```

```{r correlation-model-output}
pretty_table(corr_estimates, caption = "Model-estimated condition means: correlation absolute error")
pretty_table(model_fixed_effect_table(m_corr), caption = "Full model results: correlation absolute error")
```

```{r correlation-model-plot}
plot_participant_with_model(
  participant_df = corr_participant,
  estimate_df = corr_estimates,
  y_col = "mean_abs_error",
  y_label = "Mean absolute error",
  title = "Correlation estimation error by condition",
  subtitle = "Colored points are participant means; black points are model-estimated condition means."
)
```

```{r correlation-model-interpretation}
corr_rank <- corr_estimates |>
  arrange(estimate_value)

cat(
  '<div class="note-box">',
  '<p><strong>How I read this.</strong> For correlation value estimation, the most useful result is the condition mean pattern rather than any single coefficient. ',
  'The lowest estimated error is for <strong>', corr_rank$Condition[1], '</strong> and the highest estimated error is for <strong>', corr_rank$Condition[nrow(corr_rank)], '</strong>. ',
