# Working summary

This report separates correlation and slope value estimation because the two outcomes may reflect different skills. I would read the results in this order:

1. Start with participant-level error plots to see whether condition means are large relative to participant variability.
2. Use the separate correlation and slope models for the main condition estimates.
3. Use the prior-knowledge models to check whether baseline definitions explain the pattern.
4. Use the bootstrap intervals as a robustness check for how stable the condition differences look at the participant level.

A cautious summary should focus on whether the same condition pattern appears across raw participant means, model-estimated means, and bootstrap intervals. If the intervals are wide or cross zero, I would describe the result as uncertain rather than as a strong condition effect.

